BLOCKER: `.planning/phases/02-spectra-signal-data/02-01-PLAN.md:135`, `ThermoRawFileParser/Writer/MzPeakSpectrumWriter.cs:147` — Plan keeps the Phase-1 single-row `spectra_metadata.parquet` while `spectra_data` moves to many dense spectrum indices. That will create new metadata/data index-count inconsistencies, so the “only Phase-3 scan-facet error remains” validator claim is not credible. Concrete fix: update the minimal metadata facet now to emit one `spectrum` row per emitted output ordinal with matching `spectrum_count`, `index`, `id`, and `time`; defer richer metadata fields to Phase 3.

HIGH: `.planning/phases/02-spectra-signal-data/02-01-PLAN.md:185` — `spectra_peaks` is added to the index with `data_kind:"peak arrays"`, but the mzPeak index vocabulary/readers use `data_kind:"peaks"`. With `"peak arrays"`, readers classify the facet as `Other` and may not find centroid peaks. Concrete fix: use `{ name:"spectra_peaks.parquet", entity_type:"spectrum", data_kind:"peaks" }` and assert that value in tests.

HIGH: CENTROID ROUTING, `.planning/phases/02-spectra-signal-data/02-01-PLAN.md:123,177-181` — The single `ReadMZData(... centroid: !NoPeakPicking ...)` read is defensible only for the v1 bar if equivalence is defined against TRFP’s own single-representation mzML output. It will not match the Thermo/Rust dual-emission archive that has profile rows in `spectra_data` and centroid rows in `spectra_peaks` for the same RAW scan. There is also a facet-routing risk versus mzML2mzPeak: the Rust writer routes centroid raw arrays to `spectra_peaks`, not `spectra_data`, unless profile raw arrays are also present. Concrete fix: explicitly choose the acceptance target. If Phase 2 must match mzML2mzPeak facet-level output, route centroid scans to `spectra_peaks` only or run the actual differential. If Phase 2 intentionally keeps `spectra_data` complete for all scans, state that VER-02 facet equivalence is deferred and do not claim it here.

MEDIUM: `.planning/phases/02-spectra-signal-data/02-01-PLAN.md:84-86,124-127`, `ThermoRawFileParser/Writer/SpectrumWriter.cs:427-438` — The plan promises stable equal-m/z ordering, but `ReadMZData` has already run an unstable `Array.Sort` before the planned stable pass. The later stable sort preserves the post-`ReadMZData` multiset, not original RAW tie order. Concrete fix: either weaken the claim to non-decreasing m/z plus multiset preservation, or read/sort raw pairs before the base helper’s unstable sort / change the helper to sort paired data stably.

MEDIUM: `.planning/phases/02-spectra-signal-data/02-01-PLAN.md:143-162,191-208,221-230,263-272` — Acceptance checks are not decisive: automated gates do not run `mzpeak-validate`, Task 1 does not assert `spectrum_count == distinct spectrum_index count`, Task 2 does not validate peaks metadata counts or `data_kind:"peaks"`, and the duplicate-m/z “multiset size equals row count” test is mostly tautological unless backed by raw per-scan counts or a synthetic duplicate case. Concrete fix: add exact count/index assertions for both facets, assert index vocabulary, include the validator command in the executable gate, and unit-test the stable sort with duplicate m/z input.

MEDIUM: `.planning/phases/02-spectra-signal-data/02-01-PLAN.md:137-140,258,301-302` — Memory strategy is left undecided while full-facet accumulation is explicitly allowed. That is not safe for large RAW files and the current `MzPeakParquet.WriteAsync` only writes a single row group. Concrete fix: either implement row-group batching by extending the helper/writer, or make the prototype deferral explicit in acceptance criteria and remove any claim that large-RAW behavior is safe in this phase.

